Dear doc spatz, <br><br>
The last American war was fought in the jungles of South East Asia and we will never again see a convential war fought as we fought it there. I agree Iraq was no war as we knew it and the pride I felt was for American and for our president. A pride I did not share about Johnson in Nam, because he kept changing his views according to the polls. He had no guts.<br><br>
But,, we keep blaming those in Washington for the war in Nam. Why don't we blame them for the war in Iraq? It's the same principle. It was agression, imposed upon another county that took us to Nam and Kuwait. <br><br>
I blame politicans for the cowards that they were, but they  listened to the silent Americans who remained silent and said nothing in support of American troops in harms way.<br>
It seems that you like the professor have believed much of what has been falsely published by the press over the years. <br><br>
I saw where he posted &quot;it was known in my intelligence company that, at least in Binh Dinh province as late as summer 1968, Ho Chi Minh would win any election with his name on the ballot.<br><br>
That was pure Communist propaganda given to the NVA soldier just before he was shipped South.The soldier, however soon found out that the local villagers did not receive him with open arms as he had been led to believe they would.  I can't believe that years later we still believe that Vietnam was a civil war. But I guess that's your point of view. I disagree.  <br>
  <br>
All the gooks I shot at and we found killed in battle scenes where we made sweeps through wore green or tan colored uniforms and had proper North Vietnam identification on them. Even Hanoi admits that since January 1967 any remaining VC or any one that may have had any ties to the South were placed on the front lines and were always the first to die.  Certainly there were no more VC around if indeed they ever were after TET 1968. The initial so called VC were nothing more then Sleepers left in the South by Uncle Ho. <br><br>
We decimated the Dog lap Battalion two-three times in our area yet within weeks they were reinforced with bodies from the North. Amazingly, the after action reports and books published afterwards continue to refer to them as VC and so called local villagers fighting in a civil war. <br><br>
Often when we piled up the bodies of the enemy's we found, the local villagers identified the black pajama bottom soldier as either an NVA soldier or villagers that had been forced to join the NVA under threat of death to themselves or to their families. <br><br>
That is why many of the VC were not local villagers. They were shuffled around so that they would not run away or make contact with their kinfolk's in the villages. But the disguised NVA soldiers that came into their village promising them a better way of life and saying they were South Vietnamese as an old villager told us were always easy to identify as North Vietnamese. The Northern soldier for some reason could not speak or pronounce the language or the local village dialec and that gave them away. <br><br>
It will be years before we establish relationship with Hanoi to the point that much of this will be discovered by the media, Haoni did not hide their involvement from the start, the press just choose not to publish it but we knew it then.
